fficulties and dyslexia in a range of language contexts including EAL/EFL. The book uses theories and analytical frameworks of a critical nature to reveal prejudicial social practices, and suggests future research directions towards a critical re-consideration of current understandings of dyslexia in multilingual settings, with a view to foregrounding the potential for interdisciplinarity. The book also suggests ways forward for evidence-informed practice, and it will be a valuable resource for researchers, practitioners and students alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDyslexia. 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aSecond language acquisitionxResearch. 7aMEDICAL / Audiology & Speech Pathology.2bisacsh  adyslexia.  aliteracy.  amultilingual.  areading disabilities.  areading.1 aConteh, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElbeheri, Gad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEveratt, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldfus, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKabuto, Bobbie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKormos, Judit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Deirdre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Deirdre, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReid, Gavin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRontou, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSparks, Richard L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSu, I-Fan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTo, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4htt